"Sankar V., Daniel D.K., Krastanov A.","Carbon dioxide fixation by Chlorella minutissima batch cultures in a stirred tank bioreactor",2011,"Biotechnology and Biotechnological Equipment","25","3",,"2468","2476",,,10.5504/bbeq.2011.0058,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80053055018&partnerID=40&md5=833b1166e2d679461ea7e61fc687e96c","VIT University, Chemical Engineering Division, Bioprocess Engineering Laboratory, SMBS, Vellore, Tamil Nadu, India; University of Food Technologies, Department of Biotechnology, Plovdiv, Bulgaria","Sankar, V., VIT University, Chemical Engineering Division, Bioprocess Engineering Laboratory, SMBS, Vellore, Tamil Nadu, India; Daniel, D.K., VIT University, Chemical Engineering Division, Bioprocess Engineering Laboratory, SMBS, Vellore, Tamil Nadu, India; Krastanov, A., University of Food Technologies, Department of Biotechnology, Plovdiv, Bulgaria","Increasing concentrations of CO 2 in the atmosphere is causing severe environmental destruction to the earth. To capture the excess CO2, its microalgal sequestration is increasingly being explored. This technique could become a profitable industry that would help mitigate global warming and produce a large number of value-added products like pigments, carotenoids, carbohydrates, lipids, etc. In this regard, three microalgal strains viz., Calothrix sp., Spirulina platensis and Chlorella minutissima were studied for their growth characteristics. Based upon the kinetic parameters, possible by-products, tolerance to CO 2, etc., the best strain was selected for further studies. The optimum pH, photoperiod, nitrate concentration and light intensity for this strain were experimentally determined. Also, studies were conducted with and without baffles, with varying aeration rates and with two different impellers and i.e., marine propeller and disc turbine impeller, in the presence of air alone and a mixture containing air with 15% CO 2. Among the three strains studied, C. minutissima was found to be the best strain for further work. It has maximum biomass productivity at pH 6, photoperiod of 14 h light:10 h dark cycles, 5 g/l nitrate and 6000 lx light intensity. Runs with baffles yielded higher biomass. Marine propeller gave better biomass yields in both runs i.e., with and without additional CO 2. Also, the optimum aeration rate was determined to be 1 lpm. The carbohydrate, lipid, protein, chlorophyll and carotenoid content of the biomass were estimated.","Carbon dioxide fixation; Chlorella minutissima","Aeration rate; Batch culture; Biomass productivity; Biomass yield; Calothrix; Carbon dioxide fixation; Chlorella minutissima; Disc turbine; Environmental destruction; Growth characteristic; Light intensity; Marine propeller; Nitrate concentration; Optimum aeration rates; Optimum pH; Spirulina platensis; Stirred tank bioreactors; Value added products; Batch cell culture; Biomass; Carbohydrates; Chlorophyll; Earth atmosphere; Global warming; Impellers; Pigments; Plants (botany); Profitability; Strain; Carbon dioxide; Bacteria (microorganisms); Calothrix sp.; Chlorella minutissima; Spirulina platensis",,,,,,"Aoyama, K., Uemura, I., Miyake, J., Asada, Y., (1997) Journal of Fermentation and Bioengineering, 83 (1), pp. 17-20; Arranz, A., Bordel, S., Villaverde, S., Zamarreno, J.M., Guieysse, B., Munoz, R., (2008) Journal of Hazardous Materials, 155, pp. 51-57; Audus, H., (1997) Energy, 22 (2-3), pp. 217-221; Baquerisse, D., Nouals, S., Isambert, A., dos Santos, P.F., Durand, G., (1999) Journal of Biotechnology, 70, pp. 335-342; Benemann, J.R., (1997) Energy Conversion and Management, 38, pp. S475-S479; Bhandari, R., Sharma, P.K., (2006) Photochemistry and Photobiology, 82 (3), pp. 702-710; Bilanovic, D., Andergatchew, A., Kroeger, T., Shelef, G., (2009) Energy Conversion and Management, 50, pp. 262-267; Cheng, L., Zhang, L., Chen, H., Gao, C., (2006) Separation and Purification Technology, 50, pp. 324-329; Chiu, S.Y., Kao, C.Y., Chen, C.H., Kuan, T.C., O